Because in Dijkstra's, once a node is processed (marked as visited), any other entries in the priority queue with higher distances for that node can be ignored. So the correct code here is to erase the current element (the one we just retrieved) from the set and then continue the loop. So in the if block:

st.erase(st.begin());
continue;

That way, we remove the already processed node from the priority queue and proceed to the next iteration. Yes, that makes sense.
